Pelican

Target IP: 192.168.153.98

Scanning



There are multiple TCP ports open on the target machine. I will start enumeration with the HTTP applications.

Enumeration

Port 8080: HTTP

This application is interesting as it contains the name and version. The target host seems to be running Exhibitor 1.0.


I Google searched the application name and found out it is vulnerable to command injection. The version used by the target machine is still vulnerable to this exploit.

Exploitation


The PoC steps to follow to obtain a shell is shown above from the exploit.


I followed the steps from the exploit by replacing the java.env script field with a reverse shell script pointing to my machine.


I started a listener on port 8443, and pressed Commit. After some time, I gained a reverse shell connection from the target machine on port 8443. Now I have a foothold on the target machine with the session as charles.

Privilege Escalation


There are interesting cronjobs.



Running sudo -l shows the binary /usr/bin/gcore can be executed using sudo. Apparently this application is used to dump sensitive information of active processes on the machine. From previous enumeration, I did find a cronjob called password-store. Maybe I can use this binary against it?


Running ps -auxw | grep root shows the process ID of /usr/bin/password-store is 527. And using sudo -u root gcore -a -o /tmp/dump 527 I dumped the content to the /tmp directory.


Running strings on the dump file shows the password ClogKingpinInning731 of the root user.


And using the password I obtained from the dump, I was able to switch to the root user.
